		<Placemark id="0285E0B39E3F539DB00C">
		<name>Prigorodnoe LNG Plant</name>
		<description><![CDATA[<p>At the <span class="hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline"><span class="whitespace-normal">Prigorodnoye LNG Plant</span></span>, natural gas arriving from offshore Sakhalin fields is:<br></p><ol><li>processed,<br></li><li>liquefied into LNG,<br></li><li>stored,<br></li><li>loaded onto LNG carriers for export.<br></li></ol><p>At the same time, crude oil (“Sakhalin Blend”) is also stabilized and exported from nearby oil loading facilities.<br></p><p>So this site is both:<br></p><ul><li>an LNG export terminal,<br></li><li>and an oil export terminal.<br></li></ul><div><hr><br></div><h1>The process step-by-step<br></h1><h2>1️⃣ Gas arrives by pipeline<br></h2><p>Gas comes from offshore fields:<br></p><ul><li>Lunskoye,<br></li><li>Piltun-Astokhskoye.<br></li></ul><p>It travels through the long north-south Sakhalin pipelines.<br></p><p>When it arrives at Prigorodnoye:<br></p><ul><li>pressure is adjusted,<br></li><li>impurities are removed,<br></li><li>gas is prepared for liquefaction.<br></li></ul><div><hr><br></div><h2>2️⃣ Gas treatment<br></h2><p>Before becoming LNG, the gas must be cleaned.<br></p><p>They remove:<br></p><ul><li>water,<br></li><li>CO₂,<br></li><li>sulfur compounds,<br></li><li>heavy hydrocarbons.<br></li></ul><p><br></p><div>Why?<br></div><div>Because if impurities remain:<br></div><p><br></p><ul><li>pipelines can freeze,<br></li><li>LNG equipment can be damaged,<br></li><li>ice crystals can form at cryogenic temperatures.<br></li></ul><div><hr><br></div><h2>3️⃣ Liquefaction<br></h2><p>This is the core of the plant.<br></p><p>The methane-rich gas is cooled to around:<br></p><p><span class="inline-block align-middle"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">T</span><span class="mrel">≈</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">−</span><span class="mord">16</span><span class="mord"><span class="mord">2</span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mbin mtight">∘</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mord mathnormal">C</span></span></span></span></span><br></p><p>At this temperature:<br></p><ul><li>natural gas becomes liquid,<br></li><li>volume shrinks about 600 times.<br></li></ul><p>This makes marine transport economically possible.<br></p><div><hr><br></div><h2>4️⃣ LNG storage<br></h2><p>The LNG is then stored in giant insulated tanks.<br></p><p>On Google Earth you can clearly see:<br></p><ul><li>huge circular tanks,<br></li><li>loading arms,<br></li><li>cryogenic infrastructure.<br></li></ul><p>The LNG remains extremely cold until export.<br></p><div><hr><br></div><h2>5️⃣ LNG export<br></h2><p>LNG carriers dock at the jetty.<br></p><p>The LNG is pumped into ships and exported mainly to:<br></p><ul><li>Japan,<br></li><li>South Korea,<br></li><li>China.<br></li></ul><p>Because Sakhalin is geographically close to Japan, shipping times are short compared with:<br></p><ul><li>Qatar,<br></li><li>US Gulf Coast,<br></li><li>Australia.<br></li></ul><div><hr><br></div><h1>What about the oil?<br></h1><div><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 300; letter-spacing: -0.36px; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; white-space: normal; text-decoration-thickness: initial; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial; float: none; display: inline;"><span class="font" style="font-family:AkkuratPro-regular"><span class="size" style="font-size:18px">Sakhalin Blend is a light, sweet crude produced as a by-product of LNG production from the Sakhalin-2 project, managed by Sakhalin Energy, which is majority owned by Russia's state-owned Gazprom. Minority stakes are held by Japan's Mitsui &amp; Co. and Mitsubishi Corp.</span></span></span><br></div><p>At the same complex:<br></p><ul><li>crude oil is separated and stabilized,<br></li><li>stored in oil tanks,<br></li><li>loaded onto conventional oil tankers.<br></li></ul><p>This crude is called:<br></p><blockquote><p>Sakhalin Blend.<br></p></blockquote><p>The tanker mentioned in your article loaded there.<br></p><h1>Why the project is strategically important<br></h1><p>The <span class="hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline"><span class="whitespace-normal">Sakhalin-2 Project</span></span> is one of Russia’s most important Asian energy export hubs because it connects:<br></p><ul><li>offshore production,<br></li><li>pipelines,<br></li><li>LNG,<br></li><li>crude exports,<br></li><li>Asian buyers.<br></li></ul><p>For Japan specifically:<br></p><ul><li>it is nearby,<br></li><li>reliable,<br></li><li><div>already partly Japanese-owned through:<br></div><ul><li><span class="hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline"><span class="whitespace-normal">Mitsui &amp; Co.</span></span><br></li><li><span class="hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline"><span class="whitespace-normal">Mitsubishi Corporation</span></span><br></li></ul></li></ul><p>That is why sanctions exemptions still exist for Sakhalin-related cargoes.<br></p><div><br></div>]]></description>
		<LookAt>
			<longitude>142.9147644</longitude>
			<latitude>46.6328277</latitude>
			<altitude>0</altitude>
			<heading>0</heading>
			<tilt>0</tilt>
			<gx:fovy>35</gx:fovy>
