	<Folder>
		<name>Ammonia &amp; Renewables (4)</name>
		<Placemark id="0FC064381E402B29DCAE">
		<name>Renewable ammonia plant in construction </name>
		<description><![CDATA[<div>AM Green is building a 500,000 mt/y renewable ammonia plant&nbsp; with a second phase planned later. Together the project would reach 1 million mt/y.<br></div><div><br></div><div>From platts :</div><p>The important point is not only the volume. It is that AM Green reached <b>FID</b>.<br></p><p><b>FID = Final Investment Decision.</b><br></p><p>That means the company has formally decided to proceed with the project, commit capital, and move into construction/execution.<br></p><p>In this sector, many projects are announced, but fewer reach FID. So AM Green is saying:<br></p><blockquote><p>“Even if demand is slow, there are not many real projects that can supply compliant renewable ammonia. If we are ready, we may benefit from scarcity.”<br></p></blockquote><div><br></div>]]></description>
		<LookAt>
			<longitude>82.2814575150484</longitude>
			<latitude>17.01440262913634</latitude>
			<altitude>26.64753690294258</altitude>
			<heading>0</heading>
			<tilt>0</tilt>
			<gx:fovy>34.99999688960803</gx:fovy>
			<range>3207.545008665767</range>
			<altitudeMode>absolute</altitudeMode>
		</LookAt>
		<styleUrl>#__managed_style_1553559E674081E8902C</styleUrl>
		<Point>
			<coordinates>82.28033268426049,17.01535870957651,26.30636801461603</coordinates>
		</Point>
	</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="08EC5D1874402B3268C8">
		<name>S&amp;P Global Energy News AMMONIA article </name>
		<description><![CDATA[<div dir="auto" class="min-h-8 text-message relative flex w-full flex-col items-end gap-2 text-start break-words whitespace-normal outline-none keyboard-focused:focus-ring [.text-message+&amp;]:mt-1"><div class="flex w-full flex-col gap-1 empty:hidden"><div class="markdown prose dark:prose-invert wrap-break-word w-full dark markdown-new-styling"><p>I’ll break it down by market logic: what renewable ammonia is, why Germany/Japan matter, why demand is still slow, and why AM Green thinks supply scarcity helps them.<br></p></div></div></div><div class="flex items-center justify-between"><div class="flex min-w-0 items-center"><div>Réflexion durant 29s<br></div></div></div><div dir="auto" tabindex="0" class="min-h-8 text-message relative flex w-full flex-col items-end gap-2 text-start break-words whitespace-normal outline-none keyboard-focused:focus-ring [.text-message+&amp;]:mt-1"><div class="flex w-full flex-col gap-1 empty:hidden"><div class="markdown prose dark:prose-invert wrap-break-word w-full dark markdown-new-styling"><p>The article is basically saying:<br></p><blockquote><p><b>Renewable ammonia is still a young and slow market, but Europe and Japan are starting to create real demand through regulation and auctions. That could finally make projects bankable.</b><br></p></blockquote><h3>1. What is “renewable ammonia”?<br></h3><p><b>Ammonia = NH₃</b>. Traditionally, it is made from <b>natural gas-based hydrogen</b>, so it has a large carbon footprint.<br></p><p><b>Renewable ammonia</b>, also called <b>green ammonia</b>, is made from:<br></p><blockquote><p>renewable electricity → green hydrogen → ammonia<br></p></blockquote><p>So instead of using fossil gas to make hydrogen, the producer uses <b>renewable electricity</b> to run electrolyzers. The hydrogen is then combined with nitrogen from the air to make ammonia.<br></p><p>Ammonia matters because it can be used in three big markets:<br></p><ol><li><b>Fertilizers</b> — the traditional ammonia market.<br></li><li><b>Power generation</b> — Japan wants to burn ammonia or hydrogen in power plants.<br></li><li><b>Shipping fuel</b> — ammonia could become a future marine fuel because it contains no carbon atoms.<br></li></ol><div><hr><br></div><h3>2. What is the main message of the article?<br></h3><p>The CEO of AM Green is saying:<br></p><blockquote><p>“Demand has been slow, but now regulation is finally creating real buyers.”<br></p></blockquote><p>Until now, many green ammonia projects were announced, but buyers were hesitant because green ammonia is expensive. The industry needed clear rules forcing or incentivizing companies to buy low-carbon hydrogen/ammonia.<br></p><p>The article says <b>2026 could be an inflection point</b> because:<br></p><ul><li><b>Germany adopted RFNBO mandates</b>.<br></li><li><b>Japan’s LTDA auction supports hydrogen/ammonia power projects</b>.<br></li><li>The <b>IMO Net-Zero Framework</b> could create global demand from shipping if adopted.<br></li></ul><div><hr><br></div><h3>3. What are RFNBOs?<br></h3><p><b>RFNBO = Renewable Fuels of Non-Biological Origin.</b><br></p><p>In simple terms:<br></p><blockquote><p>RFNBOs are renewable fuels made from renewable electricity, not from biomass.<br></p></blockquote><p>Examples:<br></p><ul><li>green hydrogen,<br></li><li>green ammonia,<br></li><li>e-methanol,<br></li><li>synthetic e-fuels.<br></li></ul><p>The EU rules define when hydrogen or hydrogen-based fuels can count as RFNBOs. The European Commission says these rules include <b>additionality</b>, plus <b>temporal and geographic correlation</b> between hydrogen production and renewable electricity generation.<br></p><p>That means the producer must prove that the electricity used is really renewable and properly matched with the hydrogen/ammonia production.<br></p><div><hr><br></div><h3>4. Why is Germany important?<br></h3><p>The EU Renewable Energy Directive III sets a binding EU target of at least <b>42.5% renewable energy in the EU energy mix by 2030</b>.<br></p><p>More specifically, for hydrogen, EU guidance says Member States must ensure RFNBOs represent at least <b>42% of hydrogen used in industry by 2030</b>, rising to <b>60% by 2035</b>. It also requires RFNBOs to reach at least <b>1% in transport by 2030</b>.<br></p><p>So if Germany implements these targets, German industry and transport fuel suppliers will eventually need compliant renewable hydrogen or derivatives.<br></p><p>That creates demand for imports like:<br></p><blockquote><p>Indian renewable ammonia → shipped to Europe → cracked into hydrogen or used directly as ammonia.<br></p></blockquote><p>This is why AM Green sees Germany as a positive signal.<br></p><div><hr><br></div><h3>5. Why is Japan important?<br></h3><p>Japan is different from Europe. Europe is mostly creating demand through <b>fuel mandates</b>. Japan is creating demand through <b>power-sector support</b>.<br></p><p>The article refers to Japan’s <b>LTDA</b>, meaning:<br></p><blockquote><p><b>Long-Term Decarbonization Power Source Auction</b><br></p></blockquote><p>This is a Japanese mechanism that gives selected decarbonized power projects long-term fixed revenue. Earlier legal analysis described it as a system offering fixed revenue for 20 years to eligible decarbonized power sources, including hydrogen/ammonia co-fired thermal power, batteries, hydro, nuclear, geothermal and others.<br></p><p>So if a Japanese power plant wins support for hydrogen or ammonia generation, it needs future fuel supply. That means Japan may sign long-term contracts for renewable ammonia.<br></p><p>The article says Japan awarded <b>516 MW of hydrogen and ammonia-based decarbonized power capacity</b> in its third LTDA auction. That is why AM Green sees Japan as a key buyer market.<br></p><div><hr><br></div><h3>6. Why could IMO be a “game changer”?<br></h3><p>IMO = <b>International Maritime Organization</b>.<br></p><p>The IMO Net-Zero Framework is about reducing emissions from shipping. The IMO says the framework was approved at MEPC 83 in April 2025, but formal adoption discussions were adjourned until 2026. If adopted, it would enter into force later through the MARPOL process.<br></p><p>The framework would measure ship emissions on a <b>well-to-wake</b> basis, meaning emissions from production, transport and final use of the fuel are included.<br></p><p>That matters because ammonia could become a shipping fuel. But the ammonia must be low-carbon across the full lifecycle. If IMO creates penalties for high-emission fuels and rewards low-emission fuels, shipowners may start buying green ammonia.<br></p><p>That is why the CEO calls IMO a potential <b>game changer</b>.<br></p><div><hr><br></div><h3>7. Why is AM Green’s Kakinada project important?<br></h3><p>AM Green is building a <b>500,000 mt/year renewable ammonia plant</b> in Kakinada, India, with a second phase planned later. Together, the project would reach <b>1 million mt/year</b>.<br></p><p>The important point is not only the volume. It is that AM Green reached <b>FID</b>.<br></p><p><b>FID = Final Investment Decision.</b><br></p><p>That means the company has formally decided to proceed with the project, commit capital, and move into construction/execution.<br></p><p>In this sector, many projects are announced, but fewer reach FID. So AM Green is saying:<br></p><blockquote><p>“Even if demand is slow, there are not many real projects that can supply compliant renewable ammonia. If we are ready, we may benefit from scarcity.”<br></p></blockquote><div><hr><br></div><h3>8. What does “supply scarcity offsets demand lag” mean?<br></h3><p>This sentence is very important.<br></p><p>It means:<br></p><blockquote><p>Demand is not growing as fast as expected, but supply is also very limited.<br></p></blockquote><p>So even if buyers are slow, the number of serious suppliers is small.<br></p><p>For Europe especially, the ammonia must meet strict RFNBO rules. The European Commission says RFNBO rules include additionality and temporal/geographic correlation to ensure hydrogen is produced when and where renewable electricity is available.<br></p><p>That makes many projects difficult to qualify.<br></p><p>So AM Green’s logic is:<br></p><blockquote><p>“There may not be huge demand yet, but there are even fewer projects able to meet the rules. Therefore, compliant suppliers could still have strong bargaining power.”<br></p></blockquote><div><hr><br></div><h3>9. What is “geographical correlation”?<br></h3><p>This is one of the most technical parts.<br></p><p>For EU RFNBO compliance, the renewable electricity and the electrolyzer cannot be completely disconnected. The producer must show that the renewable power used to make hydrogen is geographically linked to the electrolyzer.<br></p><p>In simple terms:<br></p><blockquote><p><br></p><div>You cannot just say, “I bought renewable electricity somewhere.”<br></div><div>You must prove that the renewable power is connected in a credible way to the hydrogen/ammonia production site.<br></div><p><br></p></blockquote><p>This is why the article says many Indian projects face a challenge. India has different grid zones and power prices. If the renewable power plant and electrolyzer are not in the same or acceptable adjacent zone, the ammonia may struggle to qualify as EU-compliant RFNBO.<br></p><p>AM Green says its advantage is that it has an integrated renewable power strategy, including pumped storage hydropower, to supply renewable electricity more reliably.<br></p><div><hr><br></div><h3>10. Why does energy security matter here?<br></h3><p>The CEO says buyers are not only thinking about decarbonization anymore. They are also thinking about <b>energy security</b>.<br></p><p>That means Europe and Asia want diversified supply chains. Instead of relying too much on one region, they want multiple sources of hydrogen/ammonia supply.<br></p><p>So India becomes attractive because it can potentially supply renewable ammonia to:<br></p><ul><li>Europe,<br></li><li>Japan,<br></li><li>shipping markets,<br></li><li>industrial buyers.<br></li></ul><p>The article’s logic is:<br></p><blockquote><p>Renewable ammonia is not only a climate product. It is also becoming a strategic energy-security product.<br></p></blockquote><div><hr><br></div><h3>The article in one simple paragraph<br></h3><p>AM Green believes the renewable ammonia market is close to becoming more real because <b>Germany’s RFNBO mandates</b>, <b>Japan’s hydrogen/ammonia power auctions</b>, and potentially <b>IMO shipping rules</b> are creating future buyers. Demand has been slower than expected, especially in Europe, but supply of EU-compliant renewable ammonia is also scarce. AM Green thinks its Indian Kakinada project can benefit because it has already reached FID and is designed to meet strict renewable-power requirements.<br></p></div></div></div><div><br></div>]]></description>
